text.text: A Guide to Angel

The Angel of the North. Nah, not Gormley’s sculpture up in Gateshead (as much as we rate that) - we’re talking about that area just past King’s Cross, y’know, round the corner from Highbury and Islington, sort of North-Central London. We heard the ends surrounding Essex Road were pretty bountiful so we packed our little bags and got a move on, Oyster cards and all. We’ll have N1 in a size Large, thanks.
Best for… community coffee vibes

tip.text:
First things first: the carrot cake here is a madness. So good. Beyond that, Appestat is your friendly neighbour, your creative workspace, your morning pick-me-up. With coffee from Climpson and Sons you can bet your cup of joe will be a tasty, eye-opener - the Estate blend is half Ethiopian, half Colombian.

The brunch menu is simple but tasty - expect much in the way of eggs and avocado. These lovely people are all about the community, whether its showcasing local artists for free, hosting monthly exhibitions or striving to introduce a local quarterly publication. Everyone needs an Appestat round the corner.

text.text: Neeks and the lovely folk at Appestat are all about community: creating a buzz, forging a sense of neighbourly camaraderie and fostering a space for creatives are top priorities. The vibe is great, the Climpson's coffee is delicious and the playlist has everything you want if you’re popping over for a spell of remote working. Monthly exhibitions showcase the works of local artists. Do yourself a favour and get involved in the carrot cake - it’s off the chain!
Best for... a full belly on the cheap

tip.text:
Usually we feel a little bit poorly when we see the words 'all you can eat', there's just something magical about that line that makes us throw up a little and swallow it back. But not here, not at this veggie BYOB, which provides a whole belly-full of good Indian grub for less than a tenner.

Seven pounds(ish) grants you unlimited trips to the food bar and as much witty veggie commentary as you can read. Every surface is plastered with pro-veggie posters, like 'veggies are happier' or 'go veg to boost your sex life' - we didn't believe them at first, but our veggie friends assure us it's true. And if a tasty dhal and a delicious paneer will pave the road to a multiple orgasm - who are we to say no? Would you?

Note: It's BYOB & cash only, baby.

tip.text:
This Victorian pub has seasonally-rotating keg beers and a wide selection of ales, lagers, stouts and porters. Ok, a pub selling beer is nothing new but check out the interiors - it looks like a London pub had a fight with a carnival haunted house.

They've also got a banging cocktail list (the Very English Garden is lethal), burgers from Lucky Chip and an upper floor for live music, karaoke and pub quizzes on Tuesdays. Master of all trades, jack of none.

text.text: If you like pubs with dope interiors then this is the place to hit up: the blue, tiled bar is mad fly and you’ll find all sorts of cool shit in here. Have a sip on the ‘Very English Garden’ - shit is mad potent and doesn’t taste very alcoholic so be sure to give your liver a heads up. Lucky Chip are serving up burgers and hot dogs too so that’ll help with the stomach lining.
Best for... a special dine out

tip.text:
After a slam dunk in Balham, Alex, Arthur and Tasos the 'bros' behind Brother Marcus decided to set up in Angel with a slightly more upmarket version of their brunch, cocktails and small plates triptych. Cooking up his Greek family flavours, Tasos lays on a spread of delicate-but-punchy small plates - full of colour and personality. A dish of marinated sardines here, a few hunks of buttermilk spiced chicken with muhammara (red pepper dip) there, and finally, with some perfectly tendered lamb chops he had us in the palm of his hand.

Placed on the mighty cute, pedestrianised Camden Passage - Brother Marcus' outdoor tables and window seats are prime for people and dog watching alike. Pair that with a tidy list of cocktails (Cherry Bomb, we will never forget you) and you've got the makings of a quality first date.

text.text: After a slam dunk in Balham, Alex, Arthur and Tasos - the 'bros' behind Brother Marcus - are doing bits in Angel with a slightly more upmarket version of their brunch, cocktails and small plates triptych. Cooking up his Greek family flavours, Tasos lays on a spread of delicate-but-punchy small plates: a dish of marinated sardines here, a few hunks of buttermilk spiced chicken with muhammara (red pepper dip) there, and finally, some perfectly tendered lamb chops to seal the deal. A classic date night spot.
Best for... cocktails with chemistry

tip.text:
It's not the size that matters: this tiny cocktail bar may just be one small room but it's full of surprises. Modelled on a 1950s film noir aesthetic, this classy joint brings science and artistry together swimmingly. The mixologists are seriously dedicated to their craft - catch them rocking lab coats, always ready to wax lyrical about every detail of their drinks.

This is where owner and cocktail-mad scientist Tony Conigliaro (also head honcho at Bar Termini and Untitled, among others) first came to prominence, and his esoteric mixology style is very much reflected on the menu (Cognac infused with frankincense, anyone?). The drinks here are inventive, potent and impressive in equal measure - take The Prairie Oyster, which is served in a porcelain shell with horseradish vodka, sherry, shallots and pepper sauce. Catch Maurice on the keys in the evenings, recreating the jazzy atmosphere of speakeasies from days gone by.

Best for… sharing and caring

tip.text:
Set up by the hugely successful Chef Director of Polpo, this neighbourhood restaurant in Islington is tickling all of our many pickles. Downstairs you'll find a no reservation cafe and upstairs there's a bistro serving seasonal sharing plates with a European influence. The menu changes daily and you can expect to discover gems such as Welsh veal tonnato, lamb and almond meatballs and peach and cow curd panzanella.

The wine list here is updated in accordance with the food menu, ensuring the glasses and bottles on offer are most suitable for what you're eating. Given the quality of food and feel of the place, you'll be hard pressed to find a more reasonably priced fine(ish) dining experience.

text.text: Oldroyd is all about European sharing plates in a snug restaurant that feels more like a friend’s living room than a public eating establishment. This is how you eat proper food - reasonable prices, quality ingredients, unpretentious setting; just how it should be. Tom Oldroyd was Chef Director of the Polpo Group so he knows the deal when it comes to gorgeous Mediterranean plates and suitable wine pairings. Cosy up with a glass of vino, wear your eating pants and tuck in.
Best for… a crafty pub session

tip.text:
Can all the real craft beer lovers please stand up. Look around, get a feel for your location and then figure out the quickest route to this spot - the Earl of Essex is pretty low key, tucked away on a residential street in Angel, but boy are they killing it. If you love the idea of BrewDog - a ridiculously extensive selection of obscure and craft beers - but can't dig the vibe, then this is probably more up your street. The vibe is way more relaxed and effortless here.

Everything on the food menu comes with a suggested beer pairing, and we've been told they're yet to receive a complaint regarding one. The taps are cool and wooden, the beers change at the end of each barrel and the garden out back is divine. Say no more.

text.text: When you’re big in the restaurant game you marry food and wine. When you’re big in the pub game you marry food and craft beer. Has anyone ever complained about a pairing suggestion at the Earl of Essex? Hell naw. With a change of beer after pretty much every barrel it’s unlikely you’ll get bored of the taps here anytime soon and the garden out back is all sorts of swell for a day of sipping in the sun.
Best for... a cheap eat with some pals

tip.text: The winds of change don't seem to be making it as far as Afghan Kitchen. This long-standing Angel institution is a comforting presence amongst the corporate carousel of new openings in Islington - a small, two-level utilitarian space, decorated with just a few communal tables and some potted plants. But you don't go for the atmosphere - you go for soul-warming curries that make your belly feel like a gently crackling fireplace on a cold day. The cooks are dab hands in the fine art of stewing and spicing, opting for delicate undertones over in-your-face flavours. On any given day, you'll find a small selection of (mostly veggie) dishes to choose from, each one under a tenner and meant to be shared with friends you don't mind brushing elbows with. Top tip: go for half portions and try 'em all.

text.text: It's a dead simple operation in here – a couple of communal tables, and a small selection of dishes laid out on display to choose from. But simple here is really pretty dope: the daal is subtly delicious and so is pretty much everything else, with thick stews topped with yoghurt and mint or the chickpea recipes flavoured with delicate spicing. Ideal for a quick, cheap dinner with some pals.
Best for... doing cocktails like Gatsby

tip.text:
Hoxley & Porter is a time machine in the form of a bar, where sticky Sambuca shooters and Jägerbombs haven't yet been invented. This atmospheric turn of the century-style railway bar makes lots of the spirits and liqueurs it serves in-house... try their Earl Grey-infused gin!

If the cocktails make you peckish, there's a pretty comprehensive food menu with dishes like Roasted Guinea Fowl, or Tomato and Crayfish Linguine.

text.text: Forget your sticky Sambucas and Jägerbombs because this art-deco haven isn't about that. Instead, it's about delicious cocktails in a beautifully decorated adorned place that seems like you might have bopped into the Great Gatsby by accident and are about to seduce a beautiful, troubled woman at the bar. That might not happen but a pleasant drinking experience will, surely.
Best for... creole by the canal

tip.text:
Let's not get into the genealogy of Louisiana, it's confusing, ask Bey. All we know is there's some real nice flavours coming out of its mix of French, African, Caribbean and Portuguese cultures. Plaquy here is trying to capture some of this Cajun & Creole goodness.

Pop in any time for Southern comfort in the form of oysters, boiled crawfish, po’boys, gumbo stew and all-Louisiana cocktails. It's still part pub though so they'll be plenty an ale to enjoy while you push your inner art snob to the limits with the colourful and elaborate murals. (They're painted by the chef's mother, so don't be outwardly rude).

Best for… your friendly, neighbourhood organic boozer

tip.text:
For good eating with a green ethos this organic gastro pub strives to centre sustainability at the heart of its dining experience. This welcoming pub's homely yet spacious design comforts those on a quick lunch break or those who would rather take their time and savour the enticing all-organic extravaganza of food and wine.

Regulars love the vegetarian platter, which features a selection of raw, seasonal veg and a range of dips. While ethically sourced meat and fish dishes are available here too, it's no wonder their tagline is "live life on the veg," as this spot is a real symbol of millennial morality.

text.text: You know you’re a new age type of pub when your motto is “live life on the veg.” The beers on offer here are organic for the most part, and if they’re not then they promise to be very local - sitting on a drinks list next to organic and biodynamic wines (of course). The kitchen here is all about simple, tasty food - the veg platter is a fan favourite and features seasonal raw veg with dips. Ethically sourced fish and organic meat dishes are also available.
Best for... a pub with some quirk

tip.text:
The Island Queen is a warm hug of a boozer - as comforting as a visit to a favoured aunt who has an ample bosom, questionable taste, and is more than capable of knocking out a mean Sunday lunch. No boundaries are being broken, but it's a charming all-rounder with geeky pub quizzes, an extensive (potentially hazardous) gin selection, and elevated pub grub that's a warm treat for the soul - keep your eyes peeled for a fantastic bangers and mash.

The slightly eclectic ‘are we in a Roald Dahl book?’ decor somehow manages to balance some of that classic pubby wood paneling and vintage chairs with birdcages, purple walls, chintzy chandeliers and mirrors painted with plants. If you like your pubs with a little quirk, then you'll be soppy for the Island Queen.
